.g., factor a shared \\\\\\\"prepare once\\\\\\\" helper, or add an extraction variant that assumes preparation already occurred).\\\\n```suggestion\\\\n\\\\tmodifiedFiles := s.resolveFilesTouched(ctx, state)\\\\n\\\\tif len(modifiedFiles) == 0 {\\\\n\\\\t\\\\tlogging.Debug(logCtx, \\\\\\\"live transcript check: no modified files from live transcript\\\\\\\",\\\\n\\\\t\\\\t\\\\tslog.String(\\\\\\\"session_id\\\\\\\", state.SessionID),\\\\n\\\\t\\\\t)\\\\n```\\\",\\n      \\\"created_at\\\": \\\"2026-03-04T04:19:56Z\\\"\\n    }\\n  ]\\n}\",\"stderr\":\"\",\"interrupted\":false,\"isImage\":false,\"noOutputExpected\":false},\"sourceToolAssistantUUID\":\"891332c2-6c86-4732-9cca-c87879c9f348\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"1d43a88b-3bdd-427c-931f-b1aefe01d503\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/2\",\"sessionId\":\"19d1c506-72ed-4b7d-b66c-fb6506c3a021\",\"version\":\"2.1.63\",\"gitBranch\":\"refactoring-transcript-reads\",\"slug\":\"jolly-noodling-swing\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01GytG73wZUqUkViV3ZYuSdv\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"thinking\",\"thinking\":\"Both automated reviewers raise two issues:\\n\\n1. **Dropped `IsActive()` guard** (threads 1 & 3, same issue): The old code at Site 2 only fell back to transcript extraction when `state.Phase.IsActive() && state.TranscriptPath != \\\"\\\"`. The new `resolveFilesTouched` falls back unconditionally (when `FilesTouched` is empty). This could trigger transcript parsing for IDLE/ENDED sessions that previously returned empty.\\n\\n2. **Double `PrepareTranscript` call** (threads 2 & 4, same issue): In `sessionHasNewContentFromLiveTranscript`, both `hasNewTranscriptWork` and `resolveFilesTouched` (via `extractModifiedFilesFromLiveTranscript`) each call `PrepareTranscript` when the session is ACTIVE. \\n\\nThe old single-function approach only called it once. Let me apply the receiving-code-review skill here. For issue 1, the reviewers are right—the old code guarded the transcript extraction with an `IsActive()` check and a non-empty `TranscriptPath`, but the new refactored version removes those guards and extracts unconditionally whenever `FilesTouched` is empty, which could cause unnecessary work on inactive sessions.\\n\\nThat said, I need to think through whether this is actually problematic in practice. For IDLE or ENDED sessions, `FilesTouched` is usually already populated during the Stop hook, so it's rarely empty. If it somehow is empty, the transcript fallback would either find nothing or stale data anyway. The `extractModifiedFilesFromLiveTranscript` function itself has an `IsActive()` guard for the `PrepareTranscript` call, so the extra cost is just parsing the transcript. But there's still a comment that seems to be cut off here. in the old code specifically says \\\"For mid-session commits (ACTIVE, no shadow branch), state.FilesTouched may be empty because no SaveStep/Stop has been called yet.\\\" This implies the fallback was intentionally limited to ACTIVE sessions.\\n\\nActually wait, let me re-read the plan more carefully. The plan says:\\n\\n> **Site 2:** PostCommit `filesTouchedBefore:905` — File list — YES — `resolveFilesTouched()`\\n\\nThe plan document explicitly calls for replacing with `resolveFilesTouched()`. But the plan also says \\\"Pure refactoring — no behavior change.\\\" \\n\\nSo the question is: is this actually a behavioral change? Let me think...\\n\\nFor IDLE sessions: `FilesTouched` is populated by `mergeFilesTouched()` during `SaveStep()`. If it's empty, the old code wouldn't attempt extraction. The new code would try anyway, but `extractModifiedFilesFromLiveTranscript` would still work correctly — it just does unnecessary work parsing a transcript that has no new file modifications.\\n\\nFor ENDED sessions: Same situation — `FilesTouched` should be populated, and if it's empty, extraction is harmless but unnecessary.\\n\\nThe real difference: in an edge case where an IDLE or ENDED session has empty `FilesTouched` but the transcript actually contains file modifications (maybe `mergeFilesTouched` failed or wasn't called), the old code returns nil while the new code returns the files. That's technically a behavioral change, and arguably the new behavior is more correct since you'd want those files for carry-forward. But the reviewers have a point — the old code had that guard intentionally. I should restore it to match the original intent.\\n\\nNow for the second issue with the double PrepareTranscript call... from this path, c) Note that `PrepareTranscript` is idempotent — the first call flushes the transcript, the second call is a no-op or very fast since there's nothing new to flush. Actually, looking at the implementations, for OpenCode it runs `opencode export` which always executes, but for Claude Code there's no `TranscriptPreparer` at all. So the double call only really impacts OpenCode with a 2x flush wait cost. Though in practice, the second `PrepareTranscript` call would see the transcript is already flushed and return quickly, so the actual overhead is minimal. Still, it's technically a double call, and the cleanest approach would be to extract the transcript preparation into a single shared step.\\n\\nI could pull `PrepareTranscript` out of both methods and let the caller handle it, which would eliminate the redundancy but make the methods less self-contained. Or I could just accept the double call since it's idempotent and practically harmless on the second invocation. Let me think through this more carefully using code review principles.\",\"signature\":\"\"}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":6868,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":100951,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":6868},\"output_tokens\":8,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"}},